{{wiktionary}}
'''Promulgation''' is the formal proclamation or declaration that a new [[statute|statutory]] or [[administrative law]] is enacted after its final [[Enactment of a bill|approval]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Promulgate Law & Legal Definition|url=http://definitions.uslegal.com/p/promulgate/|website=USLegal.com|publisher=US Legal, Inc.|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref> In some [[jurisdiction (area)|jurisdiction]]s, this additional step is necessary before the law can take effect.

After a new law is approved, it is announced to the public through the publication of [[government gazette]]s and/or on official government [[website]]s. National laws of extraordinary importance to the public may be announced by the [[head of state]] on national broadcast. Local laws are usually announced in local [[newspaper]]s and published in bulletins or [[compendium|compendia]] of municipal regulations.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

==Jurisdiction-specific details==
{{Refimprove section|date=January 2009}}

===Armenia===
{{main|Law of Armenia}}
Bills are enacted by the [[President of Armenia]] and published in the ''[[Hayastani Hanrapetutyun|Official Gazette of the Republic of Armenia]]''.

===Belgium===
{{main|Law of Belgium}}
Statutes are promulgated by the [[King of the Belgians]]<ref>Article 109 of the Belgian Constitution</ref> and published in the ''[[Belgian Official Journal]]''. Decrees and Ordinances are promulgated by the different Regional and Community governments and published in the Belgian Official Journal.

===Canon law (Catholic Church)===
{{canon law}}
{{main|Promulgation (canon law)}}
A [[Canon law (Catholic Church)|canonical law]] issued by the [[Pope]] (or with his consent in the case of laws issued by an [[ecumenical council]] or [[congregation (Roman Curia)|congregation]]) is promulgated when it is published in ''[[Acta Apostolicae Sedis]]'', and by default has the [[force of law]] three months after promulgation.<ref>can. 8 §1, ''CIC'', 1983</ref> Laws issued by bishops and [[synod|particular council]]s are promulgated in various ways but by default take effect one month after promulgation.<ref>can. 8 §2, ''CIC'', 1983</ref> 

According to Canon 7 of the [[1983 Code of Canon Law]], ''Lex instituitur cum promulgatur'' ("A law is instituted when it is promulgated").<ref>Canon 7, 1983 CIC</ref> This is an ancient provision in [[Latin Church|Latin-rite]] [[canon law (Catholic Church)|canon law]], dating in its plural form to the [[ecclesiastical Latin|Latin]] formulation of the great twelfth-century codifier of canon law, [[Gratian (jurist)|Gratian]]: ''Leges instituuntur cum promulgantur'' ("Laws are instituted when they are promulgated").

===France===
{{main|Law of France}}
The [[President of France]] promulgates law (he may ask Parliament to reconsider the law, but only once).

===Germany===
{{main|Law of Germany}}
The [[President of Germany]] has the duty to duly promulgate and issue laws, unless the President deems them "evidently [[unconstitutional]]". The question to what degree they must be convinced of the constitutional violation to deny promulgation is hotly debated.

===Hong Kong===
{{main|Law of Hong Kong}}
Bills have to be signed and promulgated by the [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]], and be announced by the government in the [[Hong Kong Government Gazette|gazette]].

===Hungary===
{{main|Constitution of Hungary}}
Laws have to be promulgated by the President of the Republic and must be published afterwards in the [[Magyar Közlöny]], which is the [[offciial gazette|national gazette]].

===India===
{{main|Law of India}}
If at any time the [[Indian Parliament]] is not in session, the [[President of India]] may promulgate an ordinance, which will have the same effect as an Act. However, such ordinance will be presented before the parliament for final approval.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Constitution (Thirty-eighth Amendment) Act, 1975, The Constitution of India|url=http://indiacode.nic.in/coiweb/amend/amend38.htm}}</ref>

===Republic of Ireland===
{{main|Law of the Republic of Ireland}}
All laws passed by the [[Oireachtas]] are promulgated by a notice in the ''[[Iris Oifigiúil]]'' published by the [[President of Ireland]], as required by the [[Constitution of Ireland]].<ref>Articles 13.3.2° and 25.4.2°</ref>

===Isle of Man===
{{main|Manx law}}
By ancient custom an Act of [[Tynwald]], the legislature of the island, did not come into force until it had been "promulgated" at an open-air sitting of [[Tynwald]], usually held on [[Tynwald Hill]] at St John's on St John's Day (24 June) but since the adoption of the Gregorian calendar in 1753<ref>Gregorian Calendar Act 1753 {{citation | title = Statutes of the Isle of Man | volume = I | location = Douglas | year = 1883 | pages = 258–267 }}</ref> on 5 July (or on the following Monday if 5 July is a Saturday or Sunday<ref>Statutory Time etc. Act 1883 {{citation | title = Statutes of the Isle of Man | volume = V | page = 209}}</ref>). Promulgation originally consisted of the reading of the Act in English and [[Manx language|Manx]], but after 1865 the reading of the title of the Act and a summary of each section were sufficient.<ref>Acts of Tynwald (Promulgation) Act 1865 {{citation | title = Statutes of the Isle of Man | volume = III | page = 176}}</ref> This was reduced in 1895 to the titles and a memorandum of the object and purport of the Act,<ref>An Act to further alter the mode of promulgating Acts of Tynwald {{citation | title = Statutes of the Isle of Man | volume = VII | page = 1}}</ref> and since 1988 only the short title and a summary of the long title have been read.<ref>Promulgation Act 1988 sections 2, 3 and 5</ref> An emergency procedure enabling an Act to [[come into force]] on  royal assent being announced at an ordinary sitting of [[Tynwald]], subject to its being promulgated within 12 months, was introduced in 1916;<ref>Acts of Tynwald (Emergency Promulgation) Act 1916 {{citation | title = Statutes of the Isle of Man | volume = X | page = 31}}</ref> since 1976 this has been the 'default' procedure,<ref>Interpretation Act 1976 section 10</ref> and since 1988 an Act ceases to have effect unless promulgated within 18 months after  royal assent is announced in Tynwald.<ref>Promulgation Act 1988 section 3</ref>

===Italy===
{{main|Law of Italy}}
The [[President of Italy|President of the Republic]] promulgates law. The President remands a law to the Chambers of Parliament, with an explanation, and asks for reconsideration&mdash;but must promulgate the law if it is re-approved without modification.

===Japan===
{{main|Law of Japan}}
The [[Emperor of Japan]] promulgates laws passed by the [[Diet of Japan|Diet]]. The Emperor cannot refuse to promulgate a law.

===Kenya===
{{main|Constitution of Kenya}}
Promulgation is performed by the President.

===Luxembourg===
Article 34 of the constitution of [[Luxembourg]] requires the [[Grand Duke of Luxembourg|grand duke or duchess]] to ''promulgate'' a new law for it to take effect.

===Macau===
{{main|Legal system of Macau}}
Bills have to approved by the Legislative Assembly, signed and promulgated by the [[Chief Executive of Macau|Chief Executive]]. They must be published in the Official Gazette ''[[Boletim Oficial]]''.

===Malta===
{{main|Law of Malta}}
When a bill is approved by the [[House of Representatives of Malta]], it is presented to the [[President of Malta]] for his assent. According to constitutional obligation he shall without delay signify that he assents and hence promulgate the said Bill into a Parliamentary Act. The Parliamentary Act is then published in the ''Malta Government Gazette'', and thus [[comes into force]].

===Mexico===
{{main|Law of Mexico}}
A law is approved by Congress, signed by the President, and published in the [[Official Journal of the Federation|Official Diary of the Federation]] ({{lang-es|Diario Oficial de la Federación}}), or DOF. Each law in its Transitional Articles (''Transitorios'') states when the Law takes effect (''entra en vigor'') and, when applicable, what law it cancels and replaces. Regulations are prepared by the Executive branch in order to establish the administration of the Law. They are signed by the President and published in the DOF.

===Poland===
{{main|Law of Poland}}
Laws have to be promulgated by the [[President of the Republic of Poland|President of the Republic]] in the ''[[Dziennik Ustaw]]'' journal. The President may refer to the [[The Constitutional Tribunal of Poland|Constitutional Tribunal]]; if he has not made reference, he may refer the bill to the [[Sejm]] ([[veto]]) for further reconsideration. The bill shall then be

===Portugal===
{{main|Law of Portugal}}
The laws (statutes issued by the [[Assembly of the Republic (Portugal)|Parliament]]) and the decree-laws (statutes issued by the [[Government of Portugal|Government]]) have to be promulgated by the [[President of Portugal]] to take effect. The promulgation is the act by which the President solemnly testifies the existence of a rule of law and intimates its observation. The President may however decide not to promulgate the bill and to veto it with a political or legal justification. After the promulgation, the statutes are published in the ''[[Diário da República]]'' (official journal), with the laws needing a Government referenda before.

===Romania===
{{main|Law of Romania}}
Bills have to be promulgated by the [[President of Romania|President]] and afterwards published in the official gazette, ''[[Monitorul Oficial]]''.

===Spain===
Article 91 of the [[Spanish Constitution]] establishes that bills, upon being passed by the ''[[Cortes Generales]]'',  must be sanctioned (i.e., given [[royal assent]]) by the [[King of Spain]] within two weeks of their passing. The King will then promulgate and immediately publish them in the official gazette, the ''[[Boletín Oficial del Estado]]''.

===Sweden===
{{main|Law of Sweden}}
Laws and [[secondary legislation]] are promulgated by the [[Government of Sweden]] and are published in the [[Swedish Code of Statutes]] ({{lang-sv|Svensk författningssamling}}).

===Turkey===
{{main|Law of Turkey}}
Bills are promulgated by [[President of Turkey|President of the Republic]] and published in the official gazette, ''[[Resmi Gazete]]''.

===United Kingdom===
[[Act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom|Acts of Parliament]], in the [[United Kingdom]] are promulgated when given [[royal assent]] by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Queen]]. The sovereign may appear personally in the [[House of Lords]] or may appoint [[Lords Commissioners]], who announce that royal assent has been granted at a ceremony held at the [[Palace of Westminster]] for this purpose. However, royal assent is usually granted less ceremonially by [[letters patent]].

===United States===
{{main|Law of the United States}}
[[Acts of Congress]] are given the force of law, in one of the following ways: signed by the [[President of the United States]]; neither signed nor [[veto#United States|vetoed]] by the President within ten days from reception (excluding Sundays) while the Congress is in session; or, when both the [[United States Senate|Senate]] and the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] vote, by a [[two-thirds majority]] in each chamber, to override a presidential veto during its session.<ref>{{cite web|title=1 U.S. Code § 106a - Promulgation of laws|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/1/106a|publisher=Legal Information Institute (LII)|accessdate=October 28, 2015}}</ref> In [[United States administrative law]], a federal regulation may be said to be formally promulgated when it appears in the ''[[Federal Register]]'' and after the public-comment period concludes.

Amendments to the [[United States Constitution]] attain force of law "when ratified by the legislatures of three fourths of the several states, or by conventions in three fourths thereof, as the one or the other mode of ratification may be proposed by the Congress".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/constitution/article-v.html | title =The Constitution of the United states Article V | author =''[[National Archives and Records Administration]]'' | publisher =archives.gov}}</ref> When the requisite number of state ratifications has been reached (currently 38), it is the duty of the [[Archivist of the United States]] to issue a certificate proclaiming a particular amendment duly ratified and part of the Constitution.<ref>{{USPL|98|497}}</ref>

